"'''Wipe Your Eyes'''" is a song recorded by American band [[Maroon 5]] for the deluxe edition of their fourth studio album ''[[Overexposed (album)|Overexposed]]'' (2012). It was written by [[Adam Levine]], [[J.R. Rotem|Jonathan Rotem]], [[Ross Golan]], Sanjeet Singh Kang, [[Damon Albarn]], [[Amadou & Mariam|Mariam Doumbia]], Marc Moreau; the production was done by Roten under his production name J.R. Rotem. "Wipe Your Eyes" is a mid-tempo [[piano]]-driven [[Ballad (music)|ballad]] and contains sample of the recording "Cabali". [[Music journalism|Music critics]] gave the song mixed reviews; there was some criticism towards its beginning, however they found the rest of the song interesting. Following the release of the album, due to strong digital downloads, the song peaked at number 18 on the [[Gaon Chart|singles chart]] in South Korea and at number 80 on the US ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]. "Wipe Your Eyes" was included on the set list for Maroon 5's fourth worldwide tour, the [[Overexposed Tour]] (2012<U+2014>13).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philippineconcerts.com/events/overexposed-tour-maroon-5-manila-photos-setlist/|title=Overexposed Tour: Maroon 5 Manilla Photos / Setlist|publisher=Philippine Concerts|accessdate=January 23, 2013}}</ref>

== Background and production ==
[[File:JR Rotem LF.JPG|150px|thumbnail|right|[[J.R. Rotem]] co-wrote and produced "Wipe Your Eyes".]]
In 2011, Maroon 5 re-released their third studio album ''[[Hands All Over (album)|Hands All Over]]''. The lead single from the re-issue of the album, "[[Moves Like Jagger]]" featured American recording artist [[Christina Aguilera]] and was a commercial success, managing to reach number-one on 18 national charts including the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref name="huffington">{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/04/16/maroon-5-payphone-wiz-khalifa-overexposed_n_1429038.html|title=
Maroon 5, 'Payphone': Band Releases Song With Wiz Khalifa Off New Album 'Overexposed' (Audio)|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|publisher=[[AOL]]|last=Bell|first=Crystal|date=April 16, 2012|accessdate=January 20, 2013}}</ref> In middle 2011, the band started working on their following fourth studio album. One of the members of Maroon 5, James Valentine spoke to ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' and revealed their plans to release their fourth studio album in early 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/news/a335543/maroon-5-we-want-to-release-new-album-soon.html|title=Maroon 5: 'We want to release new album soon'|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]. [[Nat Mags]]|last=Corner|first=Lewis|date=August 17, 2011|accessdate=January 21, 2013}}</ref> On March 22, 2012, the band posted a video on [[YouTube]] featuring numerous scenes from the band in the studio, recording the album.<ref>{{cite web|title=Overexposed - June 26th|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yHe3gC7GsyM&feature=player_embedded|publisher=Maroon5. [[YouTube]]|accessdate=April 10, 2012}}</ref> On July 17, 2012, the album was released under the title ''[[Overexposed (album)|Overexposed]]''.<ref name="overexposed">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/overexposed-deluxe-version/id542468867|title=Overexposed by Maroon 5|publisher=[[iTunes Store]] (US). [[Apple Inc|Apple]]|accessdate=January 21, 2013}}</ref>

"Wipe Your Eyes" was written by Maroon 5's lead singer [[Adam Levine]] together with [[Jonathan Rotem]], [[Ross Golan]], Sanjeet Singh Kang, [[Damon Albarn]], [[Amadou & Mariam|Mariam Doumbia]], Marc Moreau.<ref name="Notes"/> The song was produced by Rotem under his production name J.R. Rotem, while Shawn Kang provided additional production.<ref name="Notes"/> "Wipe Your Eyes" was [[Recording|recorded]] at [[Conway Studios]] in [[Los Angeles]] by Noah "Mailbox" Passovoy and Eric Eylands served as engineering assistant.<ref name="Notes"/> Serban Ghenea [[Mixing (music production)|mixed]] the song at Mixstar Studios in [[Virginia Beach]] together with John Hanes and Phil Seaford who served as mixing engineer and mixing assistant respectively.<ref name="Notes"/> Rotem also provided the [[Programming (music)|programming]] and the [[Key (music)|keys]], while James Valentine provided the [[sitar]].<ref name="Notes"/> "Wipe Your Eyes" was included in the deluxe edition of ''Overexposed''.<ref name="overexposed"/>

== Composition and critical reception ==

"Wipe Your Eyes" is a mid-tempo piano-driven [[Ballad (music)|ballad]] with a length of three minutes and thirty-four seconds.<ref name="idolator">{{cite web|url=http://idolator.com/6630401/maroon-5-wipe-your-eyes-overexposed-track-listen|title=Maroon 5 Want To 'Wipe Your Eyes' With New 'Overexposed' Track: Listen|publisher=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]. [[Buzz Media]]|last=Daw|first=Robbie|date=June 18, 2012|accessdate=January 31, 2013}}</ref><ref name="discubed">{{cite web|url=http://discubed.com/2012/06/26/music-review-maroon-5-overexposed/|title=Music Review: Maroon 5 - Overexposed|publisher=Discubed.com|first=Scott|date=June 26, 2012|accessdate=January 31, 2013}}</ref> It contains sample of the recording "Cabali" which is written by Damon Albarn, Mariam Doumbia and Marc A. Moreau published by [[Chrysalis Music]].<ref name="Notes"/> "Wipe Your Eyes" starts with "crooning by a chipmunk-like voice", and after that Levine professes "I<U+2019>m here to wipe your eyes" to his broken-hearted romantic interest.<ref name="idolator"/> Brittany Frederick of StarPulse criticized the opening of the song labeling it as "jarring nonsensical sounds" which can also be heard in the background. However, according to her, "they're minor issues with an album that is bound to get at least one song other than '[[Payphone (song)|Payphone]]' stuck in your head."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starpulse.com/news/Brittany_Frederick/2012/06/26/album_review_maroon_5_overexposed|title=Album Review: Maroon 5, 'Overexposed'|publisher=StarPulse|last=Frederick|first=Brittany|date=June 26, 2012|accessdate=January 31, 2013}}</ref> Alt Rock Live's Keaton Fletcher in a review of ''Overexposed'', wrote that the beginning of the song makes you ask yourself "do you really want to listen to this song?" However, he concluded that after its first thirty seconds it sounds like typical Maroon 5 song on which you feel smooth sexuality.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altrocklive.com/reviews/cd/maroon-5-overexposed/112/|title=Maroon 5 - Overexposed|publisher=Alt Rock Live|last=Fletcher|first=Keaton|date=August 6, 2012|accessdate=January 31, 2013}}</ref> A reviewer of [[WNKS|Kiss 95.1]] radio wrote that "Wipe Your Eyes" together with "[[Love Somebody (Maroon 5 song)|Love Somebody]]" and "Beautiful Goodbye" are a "fan favorites" songs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kiss951.cbslocal.com/2012/06/25/album-review-maroon-5-overexposed/|title=Album Review: Maroon 5 'Overexposed'|publisher=[[WNKS|Kiss 95.1]]. [[CBS Radio]]|date=June 26, 2012|accessdate=January 31, 2013}}</ref>

